title: For Sale:  Rarest Post WWII Collectible USMC Marine Fighting Knife MSI MK2 (more rare than any Kabar or Camillus)
location: garner/clayton/40/42, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
Please know that I value your time so if the listing is still up then my item is still available for purchase. (No need to ask that question)

Click on the blue “Listings by this user” link to see all my other items.
Click on the pictures to enlarge them.

Finally, this is the missing piece to your MK2 collection. 

Here is some info on the MSI that I was able to find out:

“Hello, your MK2 knife was made by MSI (Manufacturing Specialties Inc.) in Texas on US contract sometime in the 1980's. They were actual Gov't issue knives. They were rather crudely finished as compared to the other Mk2 makers. According to Frank Trzaska, usmilitaryknives.com, he has only been able to find 1 contract for MSI for about 5500 knives making MSI MK2's among the rarest of all the MK2 knives made since WW2. They don't turn up on eBay very often. When they do, even the "tent spike" conditioned ones bring pretty good coin. Mint to NM examples w/ sheaths usually bring a few hundred dollars. I would strongly recommend against doing anything (even sharpening) your MSI knife. Frank Trzaska wrote about the MSI knives in the 10/2007 issue of Knifeworld. I hope this helps.”

"Delivery to USMC circa April 1983 the MSI example is by far the scarcest and, in my opinion, the most valuable. Made in very low numbers in the 1980s by Manufacturing Specialties of Allen, TX. The MSI knives are missing from most collections of Mark 2 blades due to their scarcity and the generalized lack of knowledge. "

Here is part of an article by Frank Trzaska entitled The Post War Knife, Combat, Mark 2 which was written before his 2007 article:

"There is one knife in the lineup little to nothing is known about, the M.S.I marked knives. The first example I viewed was in 1990 to the best of my memory. It first appeared in print in Bernard Levines Guide third edition which was published in 1993. To say they are scarce is an understatement! It took me a few years to secure the first one and from talking with other collectors I can count about seven in total. A recent purchase of some surplus knives by a collector from the Marine Corps storage in Okinawa revealed several MSI marked knives in a 1989 dated sealed wrappers. The one I purchased had the internal wrapping paper dated 1987 while the outside wrapper was dated 1989 which suggests it was a repack at some point. The knife itself was exposed to air in the packaging as when it was removed a thin film of white powder like mold was present. It wiped off easily. While this alone does not establish proof of government purchase like a contract copy would, but it firmly establishes that the MSI knife was in the supply chain and would have been officially issued to a Marine. The knives are very crude in appearance with fit and finish masked by a heavy Parkerized finish. The typical handle is thinner then normal but the other specifications all fit the bill. All observed have been black in color with typical black scabbards. Obviously made in small numbers this one continues to confuse the collecting community. If you have any information about it I would be glad to hear from you.

The M.S.I. marked knives are crude in appearance and very hard to find. The knives have black handles and black scabbards. The marking on the knives are not stamped in a straight line. The U.S. over the M.S.I is not centered correctly. This is true on the few knives observed. A real challenge to find and tougher yet to find information on."

Another MSI MK2 is currently listed for $450

title: For Sale:  SC Concealed Weapons Course Every Saturday
postcontent:
SC Concealed Weapons Permit Classes, every Saturday 9am-5pm at Blue Ridge Shooting Sports 1310 W Wade Hampton Blvd, Greer, SC, 29651. Course cost $65.00. Reserve a spot by signing up at the store. Thanks for your business.

Course Requirements

#1. Absolutely no charges/convictions for any Felonies, Criminal Domestic Violence, Drugs, or any misdemeanors that carry more than 2+ years imprisonment / probation or any charge that would prohibit you from owning or possessing a firearm. If found NOT GUILTY you should still be eligible. If you are unsure about your status you can contact SLED at REDACTED for clarification.

#2. All necessary paperwork and finger printing will be provided by me. Make sure that the address on your SC drivers license matches your current address. If not SLED will send the application back.

#3. Wear a tight neck shirt, no collared shirts please. Also bring a ball cap guys and girls. All other protective gear (safety glasses and hearing protection) will be provided by me. If you want to bring your own protective gear that is fine as well.

#4. Have a holster with at least 1 level of retention. This means a type of holster with a strap, snap, or button that secures the handgun from being pulled from the holster without being unsecured first. You must wear long pants with a belt.

#5. Bring a small to medium caliber handgun with 50 rounds of ammunition, .22 cal, .32cal, .380cal, .38cal, 9mm, .40cal, .45cal. No derringer or magnum high caliber pistols please. If you do not currently own a firearm, speak with me prior to the class and arrangements can be made to borrow one. You will still be responsible for the ammo for the borrowed firearm.

#6.The fee needs to be separated as such, $65. cash for the instructor, *Note* you can reserve a spot in an upcoming course by directly registering at the Blue Ridge Shooting Sports via $65.cash prepay. There are 18 available spots per class on a first come first serve basis.

#7. When you complete the course and get ready to mail the application to SLED you will need a $50. money order or cashiers check made out to SLED DATA CENTER CWP. You do not need to have the SLED fee the day of the class, only when you get ready to mail the application off. SLED will not accept personal checks or cash.

Most important is safety, Know your firearm prior to class, if you need to practice to familiarize yourself with your firearm or to schedule a class, call me at REDACTED or REDACTED.
Thank you for your business, Joey.
